directory: crates/ctx-scan/src
domain: Standalone CLI tool (`ctx-scan`) that builds and maintains a `.context/` tree of AI-generated file/directory summaries via content-hash (Merkle-tree) change detection, independent of git. Provides full-scan, dry-run listing, check-only staleness reporting, incremental update, and a Claude Code Stop-hook integration, all built on ctx-summarize's generic summarization runner and Fs abstraction.
edit_notes:
  - Core pipeline is walk (walker.rs) → hash (hash.rs) → summarize (ctx_summarize::runner via runner.rs) → readme (readme.rs); runner.rs::regenerate() applies changes in fixed order (changed_files, then orphan_leaves, then stale_dirs), relying on hash::diff's deepest-first stale_dirs ordering.
  - Freshness is defined solely by hash.rs's SHA-256 Merkle tree, never git state; walker.rs seeds `.ctxignore` from `.gitignore` once (never re-reads `.gitignore` after), and both hash.rs and walker.rs depend on ctx_summarize::cpath/scope_matcher staying in sync with how ctx-summarize itself paths and scopes files.
  - CLI modes (dry-run, check, stop-hook, update, full scan) are mutually exclusive and dispatch in a fixed order in both cli.rs and main.rs; adding a mode means touching clap conflict attributes, dispatch order in both files, and exit-code conventions in main.rs.
  - stop_hook must always fail open (never error out / never bill an agent session); main.rs swallows its Result unconditionally — any future logic there must preserve that.
  - fs.rs's ScanFs intercepts only read() for two hard-coded embedded prompt paths (LEAF_PATH/ROLLUP_PATH), which must match both the runner's requested prompt paths and the actual `prompts/` layout; all other Fs ops pass through to StdFs.
children:
  - cli.rs: CLI arg parsing and mode dispatch (dry-run/check/update/stop-hook), including line-format contracts consumed by external scripts/hooks.
  - error.rs: Shared ScanError type all other modules return/propagate into.
  - fs.rs: Fs wrapper embedding compiled-in prompt text so scanning works without a prompts/ directory on disk.
  - hash.rs: Sole staleness-detection engine — computes, persists, and diffs the content-hash tree that check/update/stop-hook all rely on.
  - lib.rs: Module declarations and documented public entry points (runner::*, cli::dispatch).
  - main.rs: Binary entry point; builds SubprocessAgent from env/.env and routes to cli.rs functions with defined exit codes.
  - readme.rs: Generates the human-facing `.context/README.md` explaining the tree's conventions.
  - runner.rs: Orchestrates full-scan/check/update pipelines, the seam between hash.rs/walker.rs and ctx_summarize's runner.
  - walker.rs: File discovery — walks the tree honoring `.ctxignore` scope and always-excluded/secret/binary paths.
invariants:
  - update_run and stop_hook never call the agent or write any files when the hash tree is already fresh.
  - `.context/`, `.git/`, secrets, and binaries are excluded from scanning regardless of `.ctxignore` contents.
  - Output line prefixes (`stale-dir:`, `stale-leaf:`, `orphan-leaf:`, `fresh`) and the stop-hook JSON payload are stable formats consumed by external scripts/hooks.